How many pairs of blue socks are there?<n>Output: 8<n><n>Input: How many ounces are in 5 3/4 cups?<n>Output: 7.912<n><n>Input: Which of these numbers can be written as a multiple of 19? Choices: {759, 97, 29, 19, 12}<n>output: {97, 2, 759, 19}<n>```javascript<n>const Solution = (string:string, pattern:string) => {<n>    const find = string.split('');<n>    while (find.length > 0) {<n>        if (find[0].length < pattern.length) {<n>            find.shift();<n>        } else {<n>            match = find[0].match(pattern);<n>            if(match === null){<n>                find.shift();<n>            } else {<n>                return true;<n>            }<n>        }<n>    }<n>    return false;<n>}<n>```

A good way to practice these kinds of problems while preparing for interviews is to ask the interviewer and yourself, "What is the most efficient way to solve this problem with the least code?"<n><n>#### Solution<n>```java<n>import java.util.*;<n><n>public class Main {<n>	<n>	public static void main(String[] args) {<n>		Scanner sc=new Scanner(System.in);<n>		<n>        System.out.println("Enter option");<n>        int option;<n>        do{<n>            option=sc.nextInt();<n>        }while(!(option>=0 && option<=6));<n>        <n>        switch(option){<n>            case 0:<n>                System.out.println(isEven(339));<n>                break;<n>            case 1:<n>                System.exit(0);<n>                break;<n>             case 2:<n>                System.outsy("Enter the name of the person"+2);<n>                break; <n>            default:<n>                System.err.println("INVALID OPTION");<n>        }<n>    }<n>    <n>    <n>    public static boolean isEven(int number){<n>        boolean  isEven = false;<n>        if(number%2==0){<n>            isEven=true;<n>        }<n>        return isEven;<n>    }<n><n>}<n>```<n>#### Solution<n>```javascript<n>function findNumber(numbers, n) {<n>        // Write your code here<n>        for (var i = 0; i < numbers.length - 1; i ++) {<n>            if (numbers[i] + numbers[i + 1] == n) {<n>                return {<n>                    min: numbers[i],<n>                    sec: numbers[i + 2]<n>                }<n>            }<n>        }<n>        // If does not found return -1<n>        return -1;<n>    }<n>```<n><n><n>### Instruction:Answer the 15 question(s) in Section 1.<n>

Now the person has only 3 cereal left in his hand. What percent of cereal is left?<n>Output: 85%<n><n>Input:There are 7 apples in a box. 2/5 of the apples are left. There are 4 apples in a bag. ¼ of apples are removed from the bag. There are remaining 1 apple in box. How many apples are left in box and bag together?<n>Output:<n>In this problem, we have 7 apples in the box.<n>In the 25%, we remove 2/5th apples.<n>There are 4 apples left,<n>in ¼ of the apples,<n>I remove 25% of apples.<n>Therefore 2/5 of apples removed.<n>2/5 *4 is 1.<n>Apples left 1 and in the box 7- 1 = (6)<n>Five apples are left in the bag.<n>25% of remaining apples = 1 apple. 25% of 5 = 1.<n>Therefore 1 apple is left.<n>Both apples are combined.<n>7-1+1 = 7 and 5+1 = 6<n>There are 6 and 7 apples together.<n><n>Input: On a school trip 28 students travel to the capital of another state. For every 4 students there is 1 other student. There are not as many boys as girls: there are 6 fewer boys than girls. How many boys and how many girls were there?<n>Output:<n>It says that the ratio of boys to girls is $\frac{4}{1} = 4$<n>The number of boy should be $4(4/1) - (3 \div 4) = 8$<n>The number of girls should be $28 - 6 = 22$<n>Therefore, the ratio of boys to the girls should be<n>($8$):($22

Money can be in terms of coin, notes, and credit. It facilitates bartering in the modern society which reduces time and effort in business transactions.<n>A transaction happens when a service or a good is being exchanged for another. With money, these transactions become more efficient, and the buyer pays more for the goods, or services purchased.<n>Example: In a transaction, if John wants to exchange his product to buy Mary's product, he needs money in order to purchase Mary's product.<n><n>What is the purpose of a bank?<n><n>The purpose of a bank is the storage of money, the extension of credit to different parties and most importantly to help in the growth of its account holder's money through high-interest rates.<n><n>3 questions<n><n>Instruction 1:Answer the following question question.<n><n>Instruction 2:You are required to identify any five benefits of online banking.<n><n>Question 1<n><n>You are required to identify how people use online banking.<n>Answer: 1 Person can use online banking by signing up on their bank accounts, in most banks you can use the online banking system by either by visiting the bank's website, mobile banking and the like<n><n>2. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: 600<n><n>Input: Michael makes birdhouses to sell at craft shows. He charges $22 for each large birdhouse, $16 for each medium birdhouse, and $7 for each small birdhouse. This week, he sold 2 large birdhouses, 2 medium birdhouses, and 3 small birdhouses. How much money, in dollars, did he make this week?<n>Output: 97<n><n>Input: Nalani had two female dogs that were expecting and after a month gave birth to 10 puppies each. She then sold 3/4 of the puppies after they came of age, each at $200. Calculate the total amount of money she received from the sale of the puppies.<n>Output: 3000<n><n>Input: Boris has 24 books and he donates a fourth of his books to the library. Cameron has 30 books and he donates a third of his books to the library. After donating their books, how many books in total do Boris and Cameron have together?<n>Output: 38<n><n>Input: There are 3 boxes of cereal. One box holds 14 ounces of cereal. Another box holds half the amount of the first box and 5 ounces less than the third box. How much cereal is there in all 3 cereal boxes?<n>Output: 33<n><n>Input: A jug needs 40 cups of water to be full. A custodian at Truman Elementary School has to fill water jugs for 200 students, who drink 10 cups of water in a day. How many water jugs will the custodian fill with cups of water to provide the students with all the water they need in a day?<n>Output: 50<n><n>Input:James went to the best steakhouse outside of the South.  Where is James? Choices:  A: dairy farm B: texas C: building D: michigan E: florida<n>Output:		B<n><n>### Source: https://leetcode.com/problems/easy-words-with-the-highest-frequency/<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>Solution:<n><n>```python<n>class Solution:<n>    def majorityElement(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:<n>        if len(nums) < 3:<n>            return int('0')<n>        if not nums:<n>            return -1<n>        count_dict = dict()<n>        for i in range(len(nums)):<n>            if nums[i] not in count_dict:<n>                count_dict[nums[i]] = 0<n>            count_dict[num[i]] = count_dict.get(nums[i], 0) + 1<n>        majority_ele = None<n>        if count_dict.keys()[0]!= count_dict.values()[0]:<n>            if count_dict.values().index(count_dict.values().max()) == len(count_dict.keys())/2:<n>                majority_ele = count_dict.values.index(count_dict[count_dict.values.max()])<n>        return majority_ele<n><n>nums = [3,2,3,1,0]<n>print(Solution().majorityElement(nums))<n><n>```

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. How many candiesdoescoreycleaveman?<n>Output1<n>```python<n>candies=input("candies "+1)<n>```<n><n>```python<n>Tapanga=(str(candies)+"candies "+1)"candiez"<n>```<n><n>```<n>Tapanga2="29"<n>```<n><n><n>print Tapanga<n>Output2<n>```python<n>candyTotal=int(input("enter your number "+1))<n>```<n>```<n>Tapanna2="32"<n>```<n><n>print Tapann2<n>Output3<n>```python<n>for y in range(1,3):<n><n>candies=int(input("candies in "))<n><n>c=candies+y<n><n>break<n>```<n><n>print("c in "+2)<n>Output4<n>```python<n>for i = 1<n>import 2<n><n>def  printC (num):<n>i=int(num)<n>```<n><n>print C(28)<n><n>Output5<n>```<n>candiesssss=int()<n><n>candies2=(candiessss+3)<n><n>break<n>```
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. Calculate the total amount of money she received from the sale of the puppies.<n>Output: 3000<n><n>Input: Boris has 24 books and he donates a fourth of his books to the library. Cameron has 30 books and he donates a third of his books to the library. How much cereal is there in all 3 cereal boxes?<n>Output: 33<n><n>Input: A jug needs 40 cups of water to be full. Choices:  A: factory B: garden C: supermarket D: garage E: warehouse<n>Output:		A (Dimes are sold/in the currency)<n><n>#### Solution<n><n>> ### Code<n><n>```js<n>function solve(nums) {<n>    let ans = 0;<n>    for (let i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {<n>        ans += nums[i];<n>    }<n><n>    let p = 0;<n><n>    for (let j = 0; j < (ans + 1); j++) {<n>        let q = nums.length - 1;<n>        if (j >= q) {<n>        break;<n>        }<n>        for (; q >= 0; q--) {<n>            if ((i >= q) && (j >= (i + 1))) {<n>                p = p + 1;<n>            }<n>        }<n>    }<n>    console.log(p);<n>}<n><n><n>console.log(solve([29, 29, 28, 26, 23, 19, 9]));<n>console.log(<n>    solve([<n>        "There are 3 boxes of <strong>cereal</strong>. One box holds <strong>40</strong> ounces of c<strong>ereal.</strong> Another box holds <strong>half the amount of</strong> the <strong>first box</strong> and <strong>5 ounces <strong>less than</strong> the third box.</strong> How much <strong>cere</strong>al is in all <strong>3 cereal boxes</strong>.<n>    ]));<n><n>```<n><n>* **Question:** <n>> The first line contains a number, which represents a total of the candies the friends have. The second line contains an integer, indicating the number of candies Tapanga has.<n>> <n>> *Output:* The integer output representing the number of candies Corey has.<n><n>* **Solution:**<n>For every number that goes up, the number right of the colon (`:` ) decreased by 1.<n>*For example, if we check the 13th line, 13th is a single digit, however the number right of the `:` is not a single digit!<n>*How we solve this problem?<n>    *For each pair (`<:`

If he has 20 children and 5 adults aboard the bus, calculate the seating capacity of the bus.<n>Output: 13<n><n>Input: Which month can have EXACTLY 28 and 29 days?<n>Output: February<n><n>Input: What is the value of 64 to the third power?<n>Output: 8192<n><n>Input: What time is it?<n>Output: It's 6:00<n>*/<n><n>#include <stdio.h><n><n>int main () {<n>	float sum = 0;<n>	int c;<n>	float ans;<n>	int n = 2, x;<n><n>	scanf("%c", &c);<n><n>	switch (c){<n>		case 'a':<n>			n = 1;<n>			break;<n><n><n>		case 'b':<n>			if (n == 1)<n>				n++;<n>			else<n>				printf("Error");<n>			break;;<n><n>		case '\n':<n>			printf("%s  %d", n, sum);<n>			break<n>	}<n><n>	return(0);<n>}

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. The third choice gives two of the choices. The fourth choice gives one of the choices.  Only one choice is correct.  Which one is it?<n>Output:A. The first choice gives one of the correct outcomes and two of the incorrect outcomes.  The third choice is incorrect in every respect. The fourth choice is incorrect in that it indicates that there is only one choice in the list: the second choice.  Choice: B. The first choice gives the correct result, but gives it in one of the incorrect ways.  Choice: C. No choices give the correct result, nor do any give it in the in correct ways.  Choice (D): None of the choices give the correct result or in the incorrect ways.  It is likely that there are no correct results, nor any incorrect in the ways given, but one may be in the way(s) not given.  Choice: E. The first two choices are incorrect in every way.  The third choice says only that "Only one choice is correct", which could be true or could not be true. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: 600<n><n>Input: Michael makes birdhouses to sell at craft shows. He charges $22 for each large birdhouse, $16 for each medium birdhouse, and $7 for each small birdhouse. This week, he sold 2 large birdhouses, 2 medium birdhouses, and 3 small birdhouses. How much money, in dollars, did he make this week?<n>Output: 97<n><n>Input: Nalani had two female dogs that were expecting and after a month gave birth to 10 puppies each. She then sold 3/4 of the puppies after they came of age, each at $200. Calculate the total amount of money she received from the sale of the puppies.<n>Output: 3000<n><n>Input: Boris has 24 books and he donates a fourth of his books to the library. Cameron has 30 books and he donates a third of his books to the library. After donating their books, how many books in total do Boris and Cameron have together?<n>Output: 38<n><n>Input: There are 3 boxes of cereal. One box holds 14 ounces of cereal. Another box holds half the amount of the first box and 5 ounces less than the third box. How much cereal is there in all 3 cereal boxes?<n>Output: 33<n><n>Input: A jug needs 40 cups of water to be full. A custodian at Truman Elementary School has to fill water jugs for 200 students, who drink 10 cups of water in a day. How many water jugs will the custodian fill with cups of water to provide the students with all the water they need in a day?<n>Output: 50<n><n>Input:How might a person address someone who is leaving? Choices:  A: further cause B: wave goodbye C: attempt suicide D: insulting them E: thank god<n>Output:		A<n><n>Input:What was the first amendment to the United States Constitution? Choices: A: First B: Second C: Sixth D: Third E: Fourth<n>Output: A<n>```<n><n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: 600<n><n>Input: Michael makes birdhouses to sell at craft shows. He charges $22 for each large birdhouse, $16 for each medium birdhouse, and $7 for each small birdhouse. This week, he sold 2 large birdhouses, 2 medium birdhouses, and 3 small birdhouses. How much money, in dollars, did he make this week?<n>Output: 97<n><n>Input: Nalani had two female dogs that were expecting and after a month gave birth to 10 puppies each. She then sold 3/4 of the puppies after they came of age, each at $200. Calculate the total amount of money she received from the sale of the puppies.<n>Output: 3000<n><n>Input: Boris has 24 books and he donates a fourth of his books to the library. Cameron has 30 books and he donates a third of his books to the library. After donating their books, how many books in total do Boris and Cameron have together?<n>Output: 38<n><n>Input: There are 3 boxes of cereal. One box holds 14 ounces of cereal. Another box holds half the amount of the first box and 5 ounces less than the third box. How much cereal is there in all 3 cereal boxes?<n>Output: 33<n><n>Input: A jug needs 40 cups of water to be full. A custodian at Truman Elementary School has to fill water jugs for 200 students, who drink 10 cups of water in a day. How many water jugs will the custodian fill with cups of water to provide the students with all the water they need in a day?<n>Output: 50<n><n>Input:Someone lacking immortality will one day be? Choices:  A: kick the bucket B: mortal C: dead D: can die E: dying<n>Output:		A<n><n>Input:A girl is going on a blind date? Choices: A: A blind date B: blind man C: Dates blind<n>Output: B<n>

Choices:  A: sickness B: motion sickness C: relocation D: jet lag E: fatigue<n>Output:		E<n><n>### Solution:Solution using Dijkstra's Algorithm<n><n>### Solved Questions:<n>* What does the name Dijkstra's algorithm refer to?<n>The name comes from Professor Edsger Dijkstra, a computer scientist from The Netherlands who, in 1956, first proposed the idea of a shortest path algorithm.<n>* How do you write the graph of the problem?<n>The graph is a complete graph with 22 nodes. Each node represents a single person, and between any two nodes there is an edge representing a telephone call. The graph is also shown below.<n>* What is the idea? The idea is that you can connect a list of nodes together, and if it is connected, each time you have a new node, you can check the previous 2 nodes of this new node and check whether they are in the graph or not. If any of the nodes is in the graph, then the new node is also in the graph. If none of the nodes is in it, then the new node must be added to the graph.<n>* Do you need to explain how the graph gets a unique path? The edges have weights and to get the shortest path from a source to a destination we use the Dijkstra's idea where there is no negative weight. There is a formula for shortest path that needs to find the shortest weight to get a connection from a source to the destination. The shortest path consists of nodes with shortest weight.<n><n>```<n>public class Problem34 {<n>    public static int getDistanceUsingDijkstra(int n) {<n>        // if n < 0, don't run the program<n>        if (n < 0) return -1;<n>        String[] list = new String[n+1];<n>        String[][] map = new String[n][];<n><n>        // initialization<n>        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) list[i] = i + "";<n>        for(int i = 0 ; i < n; i++){<n>            map[i] = new String[n];<n>        }<n>        for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {<n>            map[0][j] = "0";<n>        }<n>        Queue queue = new PriorityQueue();<n><n>        for (int k = 0 ;

If the result is then increased by 3, what is the remainder from the division of the number by 9?<n>Output: 8<n><n>Input: If the sum of a whole number’s digits is divisible by 5, what is the value of the 5 digit number?<n>Output: 0<n><n>Input: If you divide the value of a 20 digit number by any of its digits, the remainder is that digit. Otherwise you get zero. For example if you're dividing by three and you get seven you get a remainder of seven and if you get zero you got the quotient. If the number is divided by two, the remainder is that of the highest digit. If the number is divides by three, the remainder is that which is the lowest digit, if the number is divided by four, the highest digit is the remainder and so on, so that the number is even. What is the remainder if the number is divided only by two?<n>Output: The value of the 10th digit of the original number.<n><n>Input: Each time you subtract from three a number that is a factor of 3, the remainder is a factor of 12. What is the highest possible value of the remainder for your first addition operation?<n>Output: A number such that the sum is a multiple of 12. It is: `*13`<n><n>Input: What is the highest possible remainder from the division of your number by 4?<n>Output: A value between 9

Then an if, that checks, if the countdown is below 2 (since 2 is less than 6) the else branch of the if statement is executed. I.e. it executes the println statement that will print the correct answer.<n><n>### Explanation:<n><n>How to solve this type of problem<n><n>- read the code from top to down<n><n>- pay attention to the values used<n><n>### Credits<n><n>- [Davey](https://github.com/iamdaveysong)
